@@ -415,6 +415,33 @@ require("codecompanion").setup({
 ```
 
 
+### GitHub Copilot
+
+By default, CodeCompanion uses the standard `github.com` Copilot API. If you are on a **GitHub Enterprise** plan, you can point the adapter at your GHE instance by setting `github_enterprise_url` in the adapter's `env` table. The value can be a plain hostname or a full URL with protocol — both are accepted:
+
+```lua
+require("codecompanion").setup({
+  adapters = {
+    http = {
+      copilot = function()
+        return require("codecompanion.adapters").extend("copilot", {
+          env = {
+            -- Plain hostname or full URL are both valid:
+            github_enterprise_url = "ghe.mycompany.com",
+            -- github_enterprise_url = "https://ghe.mycompany.com",
+          },
+        })
+      end,
+    },
+  },
+})
+```
+
+If `github_enterprise_url` is not set, the adapter falls back to the `GH_HOST` environment variable (the same variable used by the GitHub CLI) and then to `github.com`.
+
+> [!NOTE]
+> The Copilot OAuth token is read from the same `hosts.json` / `apps.json` files that the GitHub CLI writes. Make sure you have authenticated against your GHE instance via `gh auth login --hostname ghe.mycompany.com` before using this option.
+
 ### OpenAI Responses API
 
 CodeCompanion supports OpenAI's [Responses API](https://platform.openai.com/docs/api-reference/responses) out of the box, via a separate adapter:
